///RECOMENDED
ss -tulnp           -To see all listening services
sudo lsof -i :8000  -To check a specific port 
sudo fuser -k 8000/tcp or sudo kill -9 PID



| `kill -9 PID`            | `fuser -k 8000/tcp`       |
| ------------------------ | ------------------------- |
| Kills by PID             | Kills by PORT             |
| You must know PID        | You only need the port    |
| More general-purpose     | More network-port focused |
| Two-step process usually | One-step shortcut         |


ls -la:
    This shows:
        - permissions
        - owner
        - hidden files
        - timestamps

ls -a:
    Linux treats files like:
        - .env
        - .gitignore
        - .bashrc
    as hidden configuration files
    So normal "ls" hides them while "ls -a" or "ls -la" exposes them